The Races of Azergad
Welcome to Azergad, a world of extraordinary diversity where countless cultures, traditions, and ways of life flourish across varied landscapes. The races and subraces described in this guide represent the major populations and most commonly encountered peoples of their respective ancestries, but they are far from exhaustive. Just as humans in our world display incredible cultural variety, even within common heritage, so too do the peoples of Azergad express their identities through countless local customs, regional dialects, and community traditions.
When choosing your character's race and background, consider not just the mechanical benefits but the rich cultural tapestry you're joining. A Veldtwin elf from a remote grove may have vastly different customs than one raised in the cosmopolitan streets of Thilidan. A Caekone dwarf who has spent their life aboard trading vessels will likely view the world differently than their mountain-dwelling cousin. Even within the same families, clans, and communities develop their own unique practices, stories, and ways of understanding the world around them.
Remember that your character's racial heritage provides a foundation, not a rigid template. While a Gushbek orc is likely to understand desert survival and beast-taming, your particular character might be the exception who left the dunes to become a scholar of ancient texts, or perhaps they blend their traditional knowledge with new skills learned in foreign lands. The descriptions provided here offer guidance and inspiration, but your character's individual journey, personality, and choices ultimately define who they are. Consult your DM throughout the character creation process!
As you adventure through Azergad, expect to encounter people whose ways of life surprise you, whose traditions challenge your assumptions, and whose stories expand your understanding of the world around you. Diversity is not just flavor text - it's an invitation to explore, learn, and grow alongside the many fascinating peoples who call this world home. Whether you're sharing a meal with a previously unknown clan of halflings, learning satyr tribal music, or discovering a community of mixed heritage that blends multiple cultural practices, every encounter is an opportunity to deepen your appreciation for Azergad's rich cultural landscape.
Humans
The Humans of Inazria are perhaps the most diverse and adaptable of all the races, spread across the tropical peninsula from the great capital of Thilidan to the remote fishing villages along the coast. Humans have built a civilization that values innovation, trade, and cultural exchange. Human society is marked by its rapid pace of change and remarkable capacity for both great achievement and devastating conflict. The human race truly exists everywhere - even in the most remote, extreme or unlikely places in the world.
Humans are the most numerous race in Azergad, and their shorter lifespans create a sense of urgency that drives them to accomplish great things in relatively brief periods. They are natural traders and diplomats, serving as bridges between the other races through their adaptability and openness to new ideas. Human settlements range from the sprawling metropolis of Thilidan to small farming communities, each reflecting the local culture and environment.
Physically, humans are highly variable but typically stand between 5 and 6 feet tall with all kinds of lean and stocky builds. Their skin tones vary from pale to deep brown, with hair colors spanning the full spectrum from black to blonde. Humans mature by age 18 and typically live 70-90 years, though some exceptional individuals may reach 100 and beyond.
Human Traits
Ability Score Increase: +1 to two different ability scores of your choice. At 10th level, you may add +1 to another ability score.
Age: Humans mature by age 18 and live up to 90 years.
Size: Humans vary widely in height and build. Your size is Medium.
Speed: Your base walking speed is 30 feet.
Versatile: You gain proficiency in one skill of your choice.
Determined: You can add your proficiency bonus to one ability check that doesn't already include your proficiency bonus. You can use this feature once per long rest.
Languages: You can speak, read, and write Common plus your choice of trade language: Kystri, Veldtwin, or Gotoro.
 
Dwarves
Descendants of men from the volcanic tropics of Kystriland, the dwarves are hardy, creative, and strong-willed. Grand kingdoms carved in molten mountains and complex underground communities dot the beaches found throughout the island chain. The dwarves are courageous and wise, known to stand their ground against overwhelming opposition; they make a point to keep their word, and take great pride in their ancient heritage.
A dwarf is steady by nature. Because dwarves live long lives, they are often slow in relationships with other men which they expect to outlive. Natural skeptics, they may be quick to judge others lacking strong morality or clear foundation. A wise dwarf knows that their greatest allies are ones with the temperament to hold to their virtues no matter the cost.
The tallest of the Kystriland men stand just above 4 feet tall, but are sturdy enough in stance to weigh more than other taller races, between 200 to 300 pounds or more. Dwarves have thick hair all over their bodies, with the burliest men growing long, extravagant beards in brown, black, red, and blonde shades. Dwarves are young until they reach the age of 50, then typically live for 300-400 years, maintaining strong memories their whole lives. The predominant dwarven people groups, the Caekone (see-kone) and the Guphati, have buried feud after feud for thousands of years. The two nations shift between times of peace and times of bloody rivalry. Dwarves of all kinds are welcome in most of modern-day Kystriland, though many rural mono-ethnic villages cling to their memories.
Kystriland's mountains stretch high yet deep underground and are filled with precious materials such as gold, pik (also known as white gold), and betharyl (high-quality material used for masterwork equipment). Most of the world's trade involves materials and logistics that flow through this region. Dwarves are generally fascinated by the endless possibilities of metals and jewelry attainable through the forge. The desire of wealth leads most dwarves to a life of seafaring, immersing themselves across a variety of cultures and climates.
Dwarven Traits
Ability Score Increase: +2 Constitution
Age: Dwarves mature at the same rate as humans, but they're considered young until they reach the age of 50. On average, they live about 350 years.
Size: Dwarves stand between 4 and 5 feet tall. Your size is Medium.
Speed: Your base walking speed is 25 feet. Your speed is not reduced by wearing heavy armor.
Darkvision: Accustomed to life underground, you have superior vision in dark and dim conditions. You can see in dim light within 60 feet of you as if it were bright light, and in darkness as if it were dim light. You can't discern color in darkness, only shades of gray.
Dwarven Resilience: You have advantage on saving throws against poison, and you have resistance against poison damage.
Dwarven Training: You have proficiency with the battleaxe, handaxe, light hammer, and warhammer. Additionally, you gain proficiency with the artisan's tools of your choice: smith's tools, brewer's supplies, or mason's tools.
Stonecunning: Whenever you make an Intelligence (History) check related to the origin of stonework, you are considered proficient in the History skill and add double your proficiency bonus to the check, instead of your normal proficiency bonus.
Languages: You can speak, read, and write Common and Kystri. Kystri is a mixture of various dwarven languages with added Common words, and is primarily a trade language taught to educated Dwarves. Kystri is full of hard consonants and sounds, which often spill over into whatever other language the dwarf might speak.
Guphati
The Guphati dwarves inhabit the expansive mountain chains of the greater Kystrilands. Guphati dwarves are known to be studious and ambitious with their pursuits. Gilhari architects are known to find satisfaction from constantly out-doing themselves, crafting and erecting increasingly elaborate structures and systems. According to the Caekone beachfolk, they are seen as plenty industrious if not a bit dull, remarking that their mountain cousins are often too obtuse to laugh at a simple joke. Living amongst sheer cliffs and smoldering heat, Guphati dwarves are particularly athletic and are known to be strong climbers. Guphati dwarves have light tan to gray skin, brown, red, or black hair, and black, red, or golden eyes.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Strength
Language: You can speak Guphati, a distinct language with many long words and phrases. Though common among the Guphati, it is rarely spoken by foreigners or in foreign lands.
Summit Lore: Always add your proficiency bonus when you make a Nature check recalling information related to underground or mountainous terrain.
Athletic: You are proficient in Climbing, and do not suffer disadvantage on Athletic checks made on mountainous terrain.
Caekone
As a Caekone dwarf, you'll be quick-witted, brave, and naturally charming. The Caekone dwarves are a creative people known for their shipwrights and survival instincts. Many are as well-read as they are lighthearted, enjoying deep philosophical talks in-between their bustling lifestyles. These dwarves of the coast are just as excellent traders and leaders as they are swimmers. Caekone dwarves have darker tan to red skin tones. Their hair tends to be lighter colors, including blondes, light browns, white, and light red. Their eyes can be bright, tropical shades of blue or green.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Charisma
Language: You can speak Caekone. The Caekone language is known to be loud and light in tone. It is the origin of many widely-used trading terms in both standard Kystri and Common.
Life on Water: Caekone dwarves never have a disadvantage when in combat on the water. Additionally, Caekone dwarves are proficient in Swimming and are capable of treading water for great lengths of time even while wearing light armor.
Silver Tongue: You are proficient in Persuasion, especially when in negotiations with one or more individuals.
Solkota
Hidden deep within the tropical rainforests of the outer Kystriland islands, the Solkota dwarves have adapted to life in the jungle canopy and forest floor. These dwarves are known to hunt often and are quite agile among Kystri-kind. The Solkata are famous for their ancient temples and ornate tools of magical quality, which feature mixed use of stone and wood. They are master botanists and alchemists, using the jungle's abundant plant life to create potent medicines and poisons.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Wisdom
Language: You can speak Solkota, a unique language with an ancient script. It is quite an isolated language and notoriously difficult to learn.
Jungle Adaptation: You have resistance to poison damage and advantage on saving throws against diseases.
Botanical Knowledge: You have proficiency with herbalism kits and the Medicine skill. You can identify nearly any plant of tropical origin and know its general properties.
Canopy Dweller: You have a climbing speed of 25 feet when climbing trees.

Palcha
Hidden within the secluded Palcha Valley on Bisengal's western frontier live the secluded Palcha people. Once rulers of a mighty empire that stretched across the western reaches of Bisengal and into the foothills of the Marram Mountains, the Palcha wielded their innate telekinetic magic to dominate neighboring peoples for nearly four centuries. Today, they continue to live in small, fortified communities carved into the valley's steep walls, maintaining a warrior culture built around discipline, mental focus, and the mastery of their hereditary force magic. Outside contact is rare, as many Palcha continue to view the outside world with pity and immense distrust. However, the Palcha diaspora continues to exist in various pockets, particularly around the region once ruled by their ancestors.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Intelligence
Language: You can speak Palcha, a dialect so closely related to Caekone that speakers of one can understand the other with minimal difficulty. However, Palcha incorporates many archaic terms and formal constructions that mark the speaker as distinctly foreign to most Caekone ears.
Telekinetic Touch: You know the mage hand cantrip. Intelligence is your spellcasting ability for this spell.
Disciplined Mind: You have proficiency in one mental skill of your choice: Arcana, History, Investigation, or Insight.


Elves
Avarazhan's elves are best defined by their meekness, mystical artistry, and otherworldly beauty. Their culture is as charming as it is mysterious; few outsiders are ever blessed to experience their arcane ways. The Elves admire nature, magic, and pageantry, devoting much of their unusually long lives towards achieving unimaginable feats in their crafts. Elves see beauty in many things, particularly in nature and the earth that surrounds them. An elf's perception of intellectual ideas, such as psychology and sociology, often come from long-lived experience. Slow to strong emotional responses, elves tend to remain aloof and flexible amidst the unpredictabilities of life.
Elves are characteristically deft and nimble. Elves are shorter than humans but taller than dwarves, often below 5 feet tall up to around 6 feet in height. Their lean, wiry frames typically weigh in-between 100 to 145 pounds. The dichotomy of sizes between men and women are quite minor; a brother may not be much taller or heavier than his sister, if at all.
Elven society famously exists amidst remote environments far away from the other races. Out of respect for nature, elves are usually self-sustaining hunter-gatherers, and typically do not desecrate their lands by clearing and plowing it. Elves from these rural communities don't travel regularly, but an elf's long life often leads to wanderlust somewhere down the road. Sometimes, elves will immerse themselves into the culture of other men, likely out of curiosity, though famous examples of cross-cultural zealots exist. These elves who thrive in the cities often ascend to high leadership roles. An elf committed to fighting the good fight undoubtedly brings incredible martial and magical skills to any fortunate ally.
Elf Traits
Ability Score Increase: +2 Dexterity
Age: Although elves reach physical maturity at about the same age as humans, the elven understanding of adulthood goes beyond physical growth to encompass worldly experience. An elf typically claims adulthood and an adult name around the age of 100 and can live to be 750 years old.
Size: Elves range from under 5 to about 6 feet tall and have slender builds. Your size is Medium.
Speed: Your base walking speed is 30 feet.
Darkvision: You have superior vision in dark and dim conditions. You can see in dim light within 60 feet of you as if it were bright light, and in darkness as if it were dim light. You can't discern color in darkness, only shades of gray.
Fey Ancestry: You have advantage on saving throws against being charmed, and magic can't put you to sleep.
Trance: Elves don't need to sleep. Instead, they meditate deeply, remaining semiconscious, for 4 hours a day (The Common word for such meditation is "trance."). After resting in this way, you gain the same benefit as 8 hours of sleep.
Elf Weapon Training: You have proficiency with the longsword, shortsword, shortbow, and longbow.
Languages: You can speak, read and write Common and Elvish. While the language between Elvish clans differ in significant ways (and are not mutually-intelligible with each other), modern simplified Elvish combines the common dialects for speaking to foreign traders and other Elves. Standard Elvish is always written in the Common script. Regardless, the Elvish languages are lyrical and poetic, supplemented by thousands of years of Elvish music and chronicles.
Veldtwin
Veldtwin elves are the most common kinds of elves. Their exceptionally thin, athletic builds and keen senses allow them to move naturally amongst the massive trees, groves and thickets of the Veldt, Avarazhan's impressively dense and tall forests. Although the veldtwin elves, colloquially called wood elves, inhabit a wide space of land, they do so in small communities hidden away from the average traveler's path. Veldtwin elves are curious and clever, often leaving their homes to join the rest of the world for years at a time before retreating to their temperate recluse. In fact, many wood elves get along so well with the outsiders that they are frequently found permanently residing among them. The veldtwin elves exhibit physical colors similar to Inazria's men, but more often include shades of copper, darker brown, or red. Their eyes are between green, brown, or bright hazel tones.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Charisma
Language: You can speak Veldtwin. Veldtwin words are short and consonant-heavy, resulting in a "choppy", lighthearted sound. Their script is simple and quickly written.
Fleet of Foot: Your base walking speed increases to 35 feet.
Mask of the Wild: You can attempt to hide even when you are only lightly obscured by foliage, heavy rain, falling snow, mist, and other natural phenomena.
Sarukhwin
Sometimes called silver elves or rock elves, the Sarukhwin of western Avarazhan's plateau region are a shrewd group particularly gifted in the arcane arts. These sagacious elves spend their long childhoods devoted to magic, particularly when it comes to the elements and astronomy. Unlike other elves, rock elves' emphasis on logic translates to a culture built on law and order. The more rigid and intellectually focused lifestyles of the rock elves often cause them to be perceived as somewhat arrogant or hubristic, unwarranted or otherwise. Rock elves typically have silver, bronze, or darker skin tones, with hair of black, blondish-white, red, or dark brown shades. Their eyes can be silver, gold, or hazel colors. Rock elves are slightly taller than other elves on average, and not quite as thin as their Veldtwin cousins.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Intelligence
Language: You can speak Sarukhwin, a complex language developed over several centuries. The script is very intricate and must be carefully thought-through, but once finished is a work of art. Spoken Sarukhwin involves many sounds.
Astrological Attunement: Whenever you make an Intelligence (Arcana) check, you are considered proficient in the Arcana skill and add double your proficiency bonus to the check, instead of your normal proficiency bonus.
Cantrip: You know one cantrip of your choice from the Magi spell list.
Tsythdaruu
Inhabiting the far eastern tundras, the rare Tsythdaruu (white elves) have existed as small, close-knit family groups for centuries. Generations of enduring some of the most difficult terrain in the world has developed capable, careful hunters. The white elves, sometimes known as tundra elves or snow elves, are known to be prudent and fiercely independent - if not a little bit stubborn. Despite this, white elves are famously empathetic and hospitable to wanderers ill-equipped to traverse the wastelands. Snow elves are thorough thinkers and naturally skilled at discerning the morality of others. They rarely have the time or motive to travel far into urban society. The relatively shorter, stockier white elves of the frozen far southeast exhibit blue or copper undertones throughout their sheet white or gray skin. Their hair comes in black, silver, mint green or bluish-white with little in between, and eyes resonating light blues, greens, grays and hazels.

Ability Score Increase: +1 Wisdom
Language: You can speak Tsyth. It is a highly unique language with very little in common to the other Elvish languages. Traditionally, the Tsyth language had no script, but has recently adopted the Common script for official purposes.
Winter Resistance: You're naturally adapted to cold climates, as described in chapter 5 of the Dungeon Master's Guide. Additionally, you gain resistance from cold-based damage.
Detect Empathy: Any Intimidation, Deception, or Persuasion check made in bad faith against you is at a disadvantage.
Sindibaan
Scattered across the northern Kystriland islands and parts of northern Inazria live the Sindibaan, a group of elves known for their agriculture, carefree attitudes, and strong history of martial mercenaries. Commonly called night elves by other Inazrian natives, the Sindibaan are responsible for orchards and farms that produce much of the world’s flavorful crops. Physically, the Sindibaan are distinguished by their robust builds and deep purple, blue-black, or rich brown skin tones that seem to shimmer slightly under moonlight. Their eyes are small and thin, ranging from deep violet to silver, and their hair is typically black, deep blue, or silver-white. 
For centuries, their elite warriors served as highly sought-after mercenaries for various kings and warlords, prized for their discipline, toughness and loyalty. Nowadays, they are a laid back people known for elaborate harvest festivals, famous night markets, and staple fruits, vegetables and fermented drinks. Sindibaan merchants are welcome in ports throughout Azergad for their high-quality goods and fair dealing.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Strength
Language: You can speak Sindibaanese, a straightforward dialect of modern Elvish influenced by vocabulary from the ancient form of Sindibaan and the form of Common spoken by north Inazrians. 
Mercenary Heritage: Choose any two-handed martial weapon. As per Sindibaan warrior tradition, you have proficiency with that weapon and gain a permanent +1 attack bonus when using it in combat.
Agreeable: Your disposition is lighthearted and easygoing, encouraging others to trust you easier. You gain proficiency in the Persuasion skill.

Kelanari
The Kelanari are a proud and ancient race dwelling within the Violet Sea itself, between the Kystriland Isles and the Inazrian coast. These aquatic humanoids possess an innate connection to their underwater territory, viewing themselves as guardians of the ocean's mysteries. Kelanari society values artistic expression through sculpture and song designed to be experienced best among the currents of the Violet Sea. Their cities are carved into coral reefs and sea cliffs with flowing architecture that mimics the movement of currents.
Kelanari are tall and graceful, standing between 6 and 7 feet in height, with lean, muscular builds adapted for swimming. Their skin ranges from deep blue-green to pale aquamarine, and includes subtle scale patterns along their arms and legs. Distinctive gill slits along their necks close when on land, and their webbed fingers and toes make them exceptional swimmers. Their large eyes are adapted for underwater vision and come in shades of deep blue, green, or silver. Most Kelanari have flowing hair in blues, greens, or silver-white that moves like kelp in water.
Generally peaceful, Kelanari are famously politically neutral. They do not interfere with the conflicts of land-dwelling men unless there is a threat to their own waters. They generally view land-dwellers with caution, understanding the value of outside contact but preferring the safe domain of their waters. For practical reasons, very few outsiders ever get to experience Kelanari lifestyles. Their long lives - often reaching 250 years - give them patience that can frustrate younger races, but also wisdom that proves invaluable in times of crisis.
Kelanari Traits
Ability Score Increase: +2 Constitution
Age: Kelanari mature by age 30 and can live just over 250 years.
Size: Kelanari are tall and lean. Your size is Medium.
Speed: Your base walking speed is 25 feet. You have a swimming speed of 40 feet.
Amphibious: You can breathe both air and water.
Darkvision: Adapted to the ocean depths, you can see in dim light within 60 feet as if it were bright light, and darkness as if it were dim light, but only in shades of blue and green.
Natural Swimmer: You have proficiency in Athletics checks related to swimming.
Storm Sense: You can predict weather changes up to 24 hours in advance with perfect accuracy.
Languages: You can speak, read, and write Common and Kelanari. Kelanari is a flowing, musical language that incorporates tonal elements mimicking whale songs and ocean currents.
Kaduran
The Kaduran make their homes in sea caves and tidal pools around the smaller Kystriland islands. Diplomatic and adventurous, Kaduran are the likely Kelanari seen on land living full lives amongst the other races. They are master craftspeople, creating intricate coral jewelry and sculptures that are highly prized by traders. Their settlements are semi-aquatic with features like tide pools and channels to bring the sea directly into their homes.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Charisma
Language: You can speak Kadurani, a mutually-intelligible dialect of Kelanari which incorporates many Kystri trade terms.
Coral Crafting: You have proficiency with jeweler's tools and gain double proficiency bonus when working with coral, pearls, or sea-based materials.
Tidal Attunement: REWORK You always know the current tide level and can predict tidal changes, giving you advantage on Navigation checks in coastal waters.
Pelagoran
The Pelagoran live aboard great floating cities that drift with the currents of the Violet Sea. These wandering Kelanari are master navigators and known to guide their settlements away from areas they predict will be hit by storms. They are known for their epics, songs which are sung by entire communities in unison, that can be heard for miles across the water and sometimes used for communication and to guide lost travelers to safety.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Wisdom
Language: You can speak Pelagorani, a highly unique language relying on various tones and clicks. It is common for different Pelagoran groups to have many differences in their language. Due to the many sounds required, it is a difficult language for non-Kelanari to learn.
Storm Calling: Once per long rest, you can cast gust of wind as a 1st-level spell without using a spell slot.
Master Navigator: You have proficiency with navigator's tools and can never become lost at sea, barring magical effects. You have advantage on Survival checks while on or near large bodies of water.
Yamaphal
The mysterious Yamaphal dwell in the deepest parts of the Violet Sea, in cities built within underwater trenches and abyssal plains. These Kelanari have adapted to crushing depths and eternal darkness, developing enhanced senses and a more reserved, contemplative culture. They are scholars of the deep ocean's secrets and guardians of ancient knowledge.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Intelligence
Language: You can speak Yamaphali, the ancient language from which modern Kelanari derives from. To outsiders, the language is poetic and formal.
Abyssal Adaptation: You take no damage from water pressure and can survive at any depth.
Deep Sight: Your darkvision extends to 90 feet, and you can see normally in complete darkness underwater.
Lack of Storm Sense: Yamaphal do not benefit from the Storm Sense racial ability.

Orcs
The Orcs of Bisengal are a diverse and hardy people shaped by the unforgiving landscapes they call home. Orcish civilization values strength, endurance, and unwavering loyalty to clan and country. Orc society emphasizes personal honor achieved through overcoming adversity, whether in combat, survival, or mastery of one's craft.
Orcs are powerfully built, standing around 7 feet tall with broad shoulders and muscular frames that speak to generations of physical adaptation. Their rough skin ranges from deep forest green to weathered grayish-brown. Their prominent lower canines and strong jaws reflect their carnivorous heritage, while their keen senses serve them well in Bisengal's harsh environments. Most orcs live 60-80 years, reaching maturity by age 16.
Throughout the last thousand years, several Orcish empires have risen and fallen across Azergad. In antiquity, it was the Dramakha empire that first rose to prominence, asserting long-lasting dominance over the other races; the conquests of empires since have all sought to regain their past glory. 
At one time, a revived Dramakha empire conquered vast swaths of human and elven territory through superior Orcish metallurgy and warfare tactics, only to fragment when the ruling clan was challenged by dozens of rival houses simultaneously. Another time, a reunified offensive built the greatest naval force the world had ever seen and controlled trade routes across the Violet Sea, but collapsed when a succession crisis turned into the War of Burning Ships. Just a hundred years ago, a seemingly stabilized version of the Empire controlled large portions of Azelliot, Zilwynbar and northern Inazria. An empowered public protested, leading to deadly resistance efforts on many borders. As Dramakha power was weakening, the squabbles of the ruling class quickly erupted into ethnic tensions between Gushbeks, Barithanis and Yaz’togalis. A new conflict exploded into the devastating three-way civil war that has left the Orcish people broken, impoverished, and confined to the hostile badlands of Bisengal today.
Orc Traits
Ability Score Increase: +2 Strength
Age: Orcs mature by age 16 and live up to 80 years.
Size: Orcs are larger and bulkier than humans. Your size is Medium.
Speed: Your base walking speed is 30 feet.
Darkvision: You can see in dim light within 60 feet as if it were bright light, and in darkness as if it were dim light in shades of gray.
Relentless Endurance: When you are reduced to 0 hit points but not killed outright, you can drop to 1 hit point instead. You can't use this feature again until you finish a long rest.
Savage Attacks: When you score a critical hit with a melee weapon attack, you can roll one of the weapon's damage dice one additional time and add it to the extra damage.
Powerful Build: You count as one size larger when determining your carrying capacity and the weight you can push, drag, or lift.
Languages: You can speak, read, and write Common and Orcish. Orcish is a harsh, guttural language with sharp consonants that carries well across Bisengal's windswept landscapes.
Gushbek
The Gushbek inhabit the scorching deserts of southern Bisengal, where they have mastered survival in one of the world's most inhospitable environments. These orcs are leaner than their cousins, with sun-darkened skin and the ability to go for days without water. They are renowned as fearless raiders and master beast-tamers.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Dexterity
Language: You can speak Gushbek, a guttural language commonly used throughout rural Bisengal that is mutually unintelligible with standard Orcish.
Desert Adaptation: You require half as much water as normal and can navigate deserts without getting lost. You do not consider deep sand to be difficult terrain.
Beast Taming: You have proficiency in Animal Handling. As an action, you can communicate simple concepts with desert creatures within 30 feet for 10 minutes. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a long rest.
Barithani
In the dense undergrowth of the Veldt, the Barithani have adapted to life in perpetual twilight beneath the canopy. These orcs are expert hunters and trappers, moving silently through the forest floor while tracking prey that would elude other races. Their settlements are built into root systems and fallen logs, nearly invisible from above.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Wisdom
Language: You can speak Barithani, a more elegant Orcish language that borrows words and phrases from Veldtwin.
Forest Camouflage: You have proficiency in Stealth. When in forest terrain, you can attempt to hide even when only lightly obscured by foliage.
Tracker's Sense: You have proficiency in Survival. You can track creatures that passed through an area up to 7 days ago, and you can identify the creature's approximate size and direction of travel.
Yaz'togal
The Yaz'togal claim the highest peaks of Bisengal's mountains, where they have built fortress-cities that guard the passes between nations. These orcs are the largest and strongest of their kind, adapted to thin air and brutal cold. They serve as Bisengal's elite warriors and are responsible for maintaining the ancient watchtowers that monitor Hyzalian movements.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Constitution
Language: You can speak Yaz'togal, a loud and harsh-sounding dialect of Orcish. It is only usually used among the upper and royal class of Yaz'togal society - speaking it proficiently is a sign of status.
Mountain Born: You're acclimated to high altitudes and cold climates. You're naturally adapted to cold climates, as described in chapter 5 of the Dungeon Master's Guide. Additionally, you gain resistance from cold-based damage.
Sure-Footed: You have advantage on ability checks and saving throws against being knocked prone.


Halflings
The Halflings of Zilwynbar are resourceful and adaptable people who have become successful despite their homeland's challenging marshes. Despite their small stature, they possess remarkable resilience and ingenuity, creating communities that blend seamlessly with their natural environment. Halfling culture emphasizes cooperation, cleverness, and making the best of any situation - traits that have served them well in both their bleak homeland and adventures abroad.
Halflings stand between just 3 and 4 feet tall, with sturdy builds and notably large ears that allow them to detect faint sounds and distant disturbances. Their skin ranges from fair to olive, often with a healthy outdoor tan, while their hair comes in browns, blondes, and occasional reds. Known for their cheerful dispositions and love of comfort, halflings value good food, warm hearths, and the company of friends above material wealth.
Halfling Traits
Ability Score Increase: +2 Dexterity
Age: Halflings mature by age 20 and live about 150 years.
Size: Halflings average about 3 feet tall and weigh about 40 pounds. Your size is Small.
Speed: Your base walking speed is 25 feet.
Brave: You have advantage on saving throws against being frightened. Halflings are used to fighting larger, fearsome creatures.
Halfling Nimbleness: You can move through the space of any creature that is of a size larger than yours.
Lucky: When you roll a 1 on an attack roll, ability check, or saving throw, you can reroll the die. You must use the new result, even if it is a 1.
Languages: You can speak, read, and write Common and Halfling. Halfling is a warm, expressive language full of diminutives and terms of endearment.
Yorokai
The Yorokai have made their homes within the massive Veldt trees, carving intricate communities into the living wood of their arboreal hosts. These halflings are excellent climbers and have developed a symbiotic relationship with the forest, serving as its guardians while the trees provide shelter and protection. They are master archers and skilled in primal magic.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Wisdom
Language: You can speak Yorokai, which includes many terms borrowed from Veldtwin and specialized forestry vocabulary.
Tree Stride: You can climb at your normal walking speed and never fall from trees unless magically compelled to do so.
Forest Friend: As an action, you can communicate simple ideas to beasts and plants within 30 feet for 10 minutes. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a long rest.
Karangala
The Karangala create extensive networks of shallow burrows throughout Zilwynbar's marshlands, building communities that exist both above and below ground. These halflings are master engineers and crafters, creating complex drainage systems and root cellars that keep their homes dry despite the soggy environment. They are known for their hospitality and their incredible cooking.

Ability Score Increase: +1 Intelligence
Language: You can speak Karangala, a rich yet complicated dialect of Halfling full of history and loanwords from many languages.
Tunnel Network: In boggy terrain, you can dig simple tunnels and burrows at half your normal speed. While underground, you always know the direction to the nearest Karangala settlement.
Swamp Navigation: You ignore difficult terrain of swamps, marshes, or other wetlands.
Gotoro
The Gotoro are wandering halflings who follow seasonal migrations across Zilwynbar and beyond, living off the land and trading with settled communities. These halflings have developed exceptional survival skills and an encyclopedic knowledge of edible plants, useful herbs, and animal behavior. They serve as messengers and guides between distant communities.

Ability Score Increase: +1 Wisdom
Language: You can speak Gotoro, also known as Uncommon. It's a language that sounds like Halfling and borrows many words from nearby Satyr, Orcish and Common, and is written in the Common script. Besides Common, it is among the most widely-spoken trade languages, acting as a lingua-franca among the northeast region of Azergad.
Forager's Knowledge: You have proficiency in Survival and gain proficiency with herbalism kits.
Cross-Country Traveller: You ignore difficult terrain when traveling on foot for long distances (more than 1 hour of continuous travel).


Satyrs
The Satyr is an abundantly common race of humanoids recognized by prevalent bovine-like legs heads adorned with grizzly hair and horns who hail from the temperate hilly forests of Azelliot. Satyrs are generally modest creatures, with a natural tendency towards diplomacy rather than violence, but are quite the energetic folk and notoriously unable to sit still. Communities of satyrs are often very large, as they crave the company of many individuals. Many Satyr tribes are animal herders and active nomads who do not settle in one place for very long; instead, they move their homes regularly once the resources of the area no longer suit the needs of their livestock. Satyrs are well-known for their exceptional hospitality, welcoming any outsider who loves music and is an easy laugh.
Satyrs are quite tall, with adults ranging from 6'1" up to 7'6" and taller. Most satyrs are also quite thin, only weighing up to 160 to 240 pounds despite their height. Satyrs often have dark brown, black, or white hair from head to toe, and plenty of thick hair on their chest and face. Satyrs typically have hoofed feet, large hairy legs, and various styles of bovine horns which differ by tribe; Their ears are pointed, longer than an elf's, and protrude outward from the skull. Male horns are much more pronounced than the female's. Like a coat-of-arms, no two families of Satyr have the same set of horns. Satyr skin ranges from dark brown to a mild tan, and eyes tend to be shades of yellow, brown, black, or green. Despite this, satyrs typically have larger features than humans, including large jaws, hands, heads and facial features. Satyrs living in large, clustered communities often take up roles as educators or politicians. In Inazria itself, satyrs are typically known to be charismatic yet influential leaders.
Satyr Traits
Ability Score Increase Increase: +2 Charisma
Age: The oldest Satyrs can live to be up to 80 or 90 years old and reach adulthood at about 18.
Size: Satyrs are slender yet quite tall compared to humans. Your size is Medium.
Fast Speed: You have a high base walking speed of 35 feet.
Low-Light Vision: Satyrs have sharp vision and great depth perception. In low-light conditions, you can see within 60 feet in shades of gray.
Tough Horns: Although Satyrs are light creatures, their heads and horns are incredibly hard and make for potent weapons. The Satyr can make melee unarmed strikes dealing 1d4 + Strength modifier of bludgeoning damage
Swift Movements: Satyrs are proficient in Acrobatics due to their naturally deft physique.
Languages: You can speak, read, and write Common and Satyr. Satyr is elegant and full of soft syllables, but is only properly spoken at loud volumes. The language of each Satyr people group is mutually intelligible with standard Satyr.
Jazikbu
The most common variety of satyr, the Jazikbu inhabit the temperate forests and plains that make up the bulk of Azelliot. The Jazikbu thrive in their native lands as aggressive hunters while maintaining a cultural sensitivity to Mother Nature's needs. Naturally outgoing and friendly, Grassland satyrs are generally welcoming towards outsiders of all kinds.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Dexterity
Language: You speak Jazikbu. Jazikbu is known to be beautiful and energetic, with a wider vocabulary than standard Satyr.
Persuasive: At the beginning of the game, you choose to gain proficiency in either Intimidation and Persuasion, reflecting a natural ability to be agreeable yet intimidating due to their horns and size.
Social Skills: You are naturally talented and able to speak or play something well without much preparation. You gain proficiency in Performance and a single musical instrument of your choice.
Lendolo
The Lendolo inhabit the underexplored wetlands where Azelliot meets the northern marshes. They live simpler, laid-back lives in stilted villages that rise and fall with seasonal floods. These pale satyrs have adapted to the aquatic environment, developing webbed hooves and water-resistant fur. They are known to be deep thinkers, contemplative artists and philosophers, creating beautiful sculptures from driftwood and chanting slow, haunting music that echoes across the marshes. A village typically consists of many fishermen and artisans.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Wisdom
Language: You can speak Lendolo, known for its poetic structure and philosophical terminology. Lendolo requires high concentration to speak, and conversations often take time due to the language's slow pace.
Marsh Walker: You can walk on water up to 1 foot deep without sinking, and you have a swimming speed of 20 feet.
Artistic Soul: You have proficiency in one type of artisan's tools and one type of musical instrument.
Borusho
The Borusho roam the foothills between Azelliot's plains and the Marram mountains, following ancient migration routes with their herds of mountain goats and hardy cattle. These satyrs are shorter and stockier than their cousins, with thick woolly coats and curved horns adapted for headbutting. Extremely proud of their culture, they are renowned storytellers and musicians. They are the keepers and preservers of oral histories that span centuries. The Borusho are famous for having incredible memories.
Ability Score Increase: +1 Constitution
Language: You can speak Borusho, a more tonal dialect of Satyr. Speaking Borusho with confidence sounds like a chorale.
Mountain Adaptation: You're acclimated to high altitudes and have advantage on Constitution saving throws against exhaustion caused by long hikes or extreme weather.
Oral Tradition: You have proficiency in History. When recalling information about events that occurred within the last 200 years, you can add your proficiency bonus to the check.


Hyzalians
Little is known from the world outside about the peculiar Hyzalian. Careful and wise, Hyzalians prefer to live in small, cloistered populations dotted across the summits of the unforgiving Marram. They certainly value tradition and deep understanding, reciting the wisdom of the past before deciding on the future.
Ancient Hyzalian literature is of a distinctly religious nature. According to Inazrian mythology, they are said to be the original descendants of Tamid'Zelnah, the being which first unified men in mind and spirit. However, the Hyzalians were cursed: a perfect creation cast down to mortality and left to think for themselves. Some Hyzalians adhere to this ancient religion even in contemporary times, though their numbers are few. 
Hyzalians are known to view outsiders with distrust. To them, outsider civilization has perverted and twisted their concepts of morality to be deeply unrecognizable. The few Hyzal that venture away from their homes often return with stories of misguided, impulsive, self-absorbed and untrustworthy men; on the flip side, the other races often consider Hyzalian culture to be primitive, rigid and conservative. Though earning their trust is a trial of its own, a Hyzalian companion is a lifelong ally.
Hyzalians are elegant creatures. Men are around the same height as humans, while women tend to be a few inches shorter. Hyzalian skin is very thick and lustrous like metal. Skin tones are various shades of gray: light and dark, and sometimes with brown or blueish tints depending on the family. Their maw is large, holding a grand set of teeth including two exaggerated upper canines. Their ears protrude from the skull significantly and are quite circular in shape. Their eyes are shades of brown, yellow, red, or violet. Healthy males are heavy and weigh between 250 to 400 pounds on average, while women are typically 50 to 60 pounds less. Hyzalians reach adulthood at age 25 and can live for many centuries.
Hyzalians are famously known for their thick, bright white hair that grows like a lion’s mane around their heads. While soft, it is exceptionally durable and difficult to cut. As per tradition, Hyzalians do not ever cut their hair. It grows until the Hyzalian reaches adulthood and, once cut, can never grow back. A Hyzalian with very long hair is held in very high esteem, while a shaved Hyzalian is shameful and not to be trusted.
Te-Hyzalians trace their ancestry to Te, who is said to be the first Hyzalian to discover darkness. Extremely little is known about them apart from stories and folklore. A living Te-Hyzalian encounter has not been documented for many centuries, though rumors and tales of their presence lingers on.
Hyzalian Traits
Ability Score Increase: +2 Wisdom, +1 Constitution: Hyzalians naturally desire understanding and truth, while their tough skin gives them an advantage in harsh environments. Their rigid skin and awkward frames restrict their movement on the ground.
Darkvision: You can see in dim light within 60 feet as bright light, and darkness as dim light in shades of gray.
Size: Hyzalians are tall and imposing. Your size is Medium.
Speed: Your base walking speed is 30 feet.
Marram Fortitude: Hyzalians are gifted climbers and feature impressive athletic bodies. You have proficiency in Athletics and advantage on checks to climb rocky surfaces.
Thick Skin: Hyzalian skin is difficult to penetrate and can be resistant to heavy blows. When you take slashing or piercing damage, you can use your reaction to reduce the damage by your proficiency bonus. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a short or long rest.
Glare Resistance: Hyzalians have adapted to a snowy life above the clouds. You have advantage on saving throws against being blinded.
Languages: You can speak, read and write Hyzalian. Hyzalians that regularly interact with outsiders and/or have an above average Intelligence score (11) may also speak, read and write Common. The Hyzalian language combines physical gestures with a variety of sounds, but is highly expressive and rich in vocabulary. None but the most studious of outsiders can speak or understand Hyzalian.

Speaking Like an Azergadling
Common Tongues of Azergad
Azergad is a diverse world full of intelligent beings that speak a huge variety of languages. Below is a brief guide to help you understand common tongues.
Common serves as the primary trade language throughout Azergad, developed from ancient human diplomatic traditions and now spoken by educated members of most races. It uses a standardized script that has been adapted by many other languages.
Kystri functions as the dominant trade language throughout the Kystrilands and coastal regions of the Violet Sea. Born from dwarven maritime culture, it combines various dwarven dialects with Common words and is considered essential for sea traders. Expect most merchants, seafarers and coastal dwellers to speak it at a basic level, at least.
Gotoro (Uncommon) serves as the traveling tongue of wanderers, nomads, and long-distance traders. Created by the Gotoro halflings, it incorporates vocabulary from numerous languages and uses the Common script. Many Common words are present in Gotoro, with varying degrees of modification, but often have different meanings. Caravaneers, guides, and adventurers learn Gotoro to communicate across cultural boundaries. Nowadays, it is frequently used as a lingua franca among the northern and eastern rural regions of Azergad, including Zilwynbar, Azelliot, Bisengal, and Inazria.
Veldtwin is the language of the Veldtwin, the predominant people group spanning the entire length of the Veldt forest. The Veldt is a forest of impressively massive trees: wide enough to fit entire towns, potentially kilometers tall, and grow in close proximity to each other. Veldt-dwellers frequently live high up in the leaves and branches of the giant trees. This is because the forest floor tends to be cold, void of useful resources, and full of dangerous monsters. Constant square kilometers of forest span the length of several nations. 
Currently, the Veldt occupies the bulk of northern Avarazhan, thins out at the border between eastern Inazria and western Azelliot, and stretches through the foothills of southern Bisengal and western Zilwinbar. This unique region has been continually administered by the Veldtwin for centuries, and thus travellers who seek to pass through it must speak and understand the language at a basic level. Veldtwin is frequently spoken as a second language by people groups that live throughout or near the forest.
Common Communication Styles
While role playing as someone from one of Azergad’s many people groups, consult this short guide for how to talk to other characters:
Direct vs. Subtle: Orcs, Dwarves, and Hyzalians typically prefer straightforward communication, while Elves, Kelanari, and Satyrs often use indirect methods. Halflings adapt their style to their audience.
Volume and Pace: Caekone Dwarves and Satyrs speak loudly and quickly, Lendolo Satyrs speak slowly and quietly, while Hyzalians combine verbal and gestural communication. Mismatched communication styles can lead to unintended offense - know your audience!
Hospitality: Satyrs, Gotoro halflings, and most humans have very social and multi-cultural societies, while Elves, Orcs and Hyzalians prefer minimal formal interaction with outsiders.
The Adventurer’s Classes
The realm is full of great evils. Most of the men and women of Inazria’s great cities and villages are the subject of great calamity. Powers and chaos out of their control will bring destruction and ruin to the land.
Unless you can stop it.
The life of an adventurer is exceptionally difficult. They are the ones tasked to go where few have dared to venture before. They are here to fight the good fight even when none else shall stand against it. 
Your character’s class is a big part of your character’s life. In Inazria, It’s less like a vocation and more like a calling - it reflects a deeper worldview, shaped by your bloodline and your environmental upbringing. And like a calling, it is often not chosen by ourselves but is laid out before us. 
There are two kinds of class archetypes your hero may choose to practice. The primal archetype represents a deeply-rooted, cultural and often biological class of origin in Inazria. It represents more than a set of skills and attributes, instead telling a greater story about the lives and values of entire clans or even people groups. A hero may or may not belong to a primal class, but may only belong to one primal class throughout their lives. A typical adventurer would start the game with knowledge of their primal abilities, but it is not unheard of for a primal heritage to be uncovered later in life. 
The civil archetype represents classes of learned skill, talent or vocation not inherently bound to a particular place or people. These classes often represent a professional livelihood with suitable skills for adventuring. In Inazria, many of the world’s peoples have migrated to the urbanized, intercultural world seeking opportunity and better lives. It is very common to abandon their primal heritage and customs (if they even know they have it) in favor of universally recognized and acceptable civil adventuring skills. Players may choose to improve their skills by taking levels across various civil classes (with some exceptions) upon improving in level.
The world’s most powerful heroes and villains usually fall into the following 8 class identities. Each one represents a framework for growth and development, as a person and as a combatant, including unique spells, feats or skills. Further, each class contains contextualizations, which are more specific choices that fully develop your character. Each character must choose one contextualization, which should be treated as that character’s primary role. As you advance in level, your class and contextualization will provide you with unique bonuses and abilities. 
Different parts of Inazria and the surrounding nations express different contextualizations of a similar class. One tribe of Berserker warriors originally hails from the plains of Azelliot - having nothing in common with branded Berserker warriors conquering the Kystrilands! Thilidani Paladins might invoke divine magic while Marram warriors call upon the great mountain-lurking beast for power. A White elf spellcaster, calling upon the deep aurora-filled tundra sky, will have different customs, skills, and abilities than one Hyzalian thaumaturge from Marlis.
Below you will find brief explanations of the 8 available classes alongside the major options available in Inazria.
