Berserkers
	In the heat of battle, the ferocious Guphati warrior begins to glow a brilliant yellow out of the ancient script-like marking all over his skin. His familiar eyes fade suddenly into something monstrous, fully intent on destruction. The air around him crackles as reality itself seems to break from his unrelenting will. Swiftly the enemy is defeated - surrender or retreat were never an option - as the Guphati combatant slays victim after victim through supernatural intensity and athleticism.
	Yet this power comes with a terrible price. As the warrior pushes deeper into their emotional fury, they begin to lose pieces of their very essence. Tactical thinking gives way to pure instinct, careful strategy dissolves into savage brutality, and individual identity rapidly blurs into the collective consciousness of all who bear the mark. 
When the battle ends and the fury finally subsides, the Guphati Berserker collapses. Over time, he is able to bear the sheer mental strain of having his consciousness scattered to the winds. It’s the feeling described as drowning in the emotions of their ancestors, like becoming a conduit for something vast and hungry watching from beyond the veil. The brand itself is no mere decoration - it is a living connection to a malevolent entity whose true nature remains shrouded in mystery. Some believe it comes from an ancient demon, others a god seeking revenge upon creation, or perhaps another being entirely. 
What is certain is the unbreakable bonds between generations of bloodlines who share the brand. Berserkers sense each other's pain, share each other's strength, and in their darkest moments, lose themselves entirely to collective fury. It is a blessing and a curse: wielding power that reshapes battlefields while forever walking the knife's edge between heroism and monstrosity.
The Guphati warrior grins, raising his blood-soaked weapon in victory yet again.
Class Features
As a berserker, you gain the following class features.
Hit Points
Hit Dice: 1d12 per berserker level
Hit Points at 1st Level: 12 + your Constitution modifier
Hit Points at Higher Levels: 1d12 (or 7) + your Constitution modifier per berserker level after 1st
Proficiencies
Armor: Light armor, medium armor, shields
Weapons: Simple weapons, martial weapons
Tools: None
Saving Throws: Strength, Constitution
Skills: Choose two from Animal Handling, Athletics, Intimidation, Nature, Perception, and Survival
Equipment
You start with the following equipment, in addition to the equipment granted by your background:
(a) any martial melee weapon
(a) two handaxes or (b) any simple weapon
An explorer's pack and four javelins
Berserker Abilities
The Brand of the Berserker
At 1st level, you bear a supernatural mark that binds you to your bloodline and grants you power through emotional intensity. This brand was placed upon you by a malevolent entity, linking your fate to that of your kin. The brand can appear as a sigil, some ancient script or other markings all across your body and cannot be removed by normal means.
Berserk
Beginning at 1st level, you can channel intense emotions to enhance your combat prowess. As a bonus action, you can Berserk, which lasts for 1 minute. While in this state:
You have advantage on Strength checks and Strength saving throws
When you make a melee weapon attack using Strength, you gain a bonus to the damage roll equal to your proficiency bonus
You have resistance to bludgeoning, piercing, and slashing damage
You benefit from any additional bonuses derived from your context
You are unable to concentrate on casting or preparing spells.
Your berserk ends early if you are knocked unconscious or if your turn ends and you haven't attacked a hostile creature since your last turn or taken damage since then. When your berserk ends, you must make a Wisdom saving throw (DC 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Constitution modifier). On a failure, you lose consciousness and fall prone for 1 minute.
You can use this feature a number of times equal to your proficiency bonus, and you regain all expended uses when you finish a long rest.

Kinship Bond
At 2nd level, your brand creates a supernatural connection with others who share your bloodline. You can sense the general direction and distance of your kin within 1 mile, and you can communicate telepathically with them within 100 feet. This communication happens in a language unique to your context.
Additionally, when a branded ally within 30 feet of you takes damage, you can use your reaction to take half of that damage instead (rounded down). This ability may only be used once every long rest.

Ability Score Improvement
When you reach 4th level, and again at 8th, 12th, 16th, and 19th level, you can increase one ability score of your choice by 2, or you can increase two ability scores of your choice by 1. You can't increase an ability score above 20 using this feature.

Extra Attack
Beginning at 5th level, you can attack twice, instead of once, whenever you take the Attack action on your turn.

Berserker Mastery
By 13th level, you’ve honed your ability to berserk and have mastered your enhanced physical attributes. While in this state, your critical hit range increases by 1 (you score a critical hit on a 19 or 20). Additionally, your berserk can keep you fighting despite grievous wounds. If you drop to 0 hit points while you're berserking and don't die outright, you can make a DC 10 Constitution saving throw. If you succeed, you drop to 1 hit point instead. Each time you use this feature after the first, the DC increases by 5. When you finish a short or long rest, the DC resets to 10.

Avatar
Upon reaching level 20, your Strength and Constitution scores increase by 4. Your maximum for those scores is now 24, and you are now considered an Avatar of your clan. Additionally, you are now able to freely move in and out of the berserk state as many times per day as you would like. Your berserk still ends when you are knocked unconscious. 

