Berserker Contexts
Gibboramites
The Gibboramites are the scattered remnants of a once-proud plains people, driven from their ancestral homeland of Azelliot into the fetid swamps at the Marram foothills. Their exile has marked them both physically and spiritually, as their connection to Gibbora has grown stronger in their suffering. The demon Gibbora is said to whisper to them through the rotting vegetation and stagnant waters of their new home, teaching them that all things must return to the earth from which they came.
Their brand manifests as dark green markings that pulse with a sickly, gangrene-like aura. These irregular straight lines crisscross their bodies like infected wounds, growing darker and more pronounced with age and battle experience. The markings seem to writhe and shift when observed closely, as if something moves beneath the skin. Gibboramites often embrace this decay, viewing their deteriorating flesh as a sign of Gibbora's favor.
The tribe's culture has adapted to their swampland exile, becoming experts at utilizing poison, disease, and the natural decay of their environment as weapons. They view death not as an ending, but as a return to the primordial mud from which all life springs. Their settlements are built on stilts above the marsh, connected by rope bridges that can be quickly severed when enemies approach. They cultivate toxic plants and harvest venom from the creatures of the deep swamp, seeing beauty in what others consider repulsive.
Game Features
1st Level - Swamp's Embrace
You have resistance to poison damage and advantage on saving throws against being poisoned. While berserking, your melee weapon attacks deal an additional 1 necrotic damage, and creatures that hit you with melee attacks must make a Constitution saving throw (DC 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Constitution modifier) or be poisoned until the end of their next turn.
2nd Level - Bog Walker
You ignore difficult terrain created by marshland, mud, or natural decay. You can hold your breath for a number of minutes equal to 5 + your Constitution modifier. You have advantage on Stealth checks made in swamp, marsh, or forest environments, and you gain proficiency with the herbalism kit.
3rd Level - Withering Touch
When you hit a creature with a melee weapon attack while berserking, you can inflict a withering curse (no action required). The target must make a Constitution saving throw (DC 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Constitution modifier). On a failure, they take 1d4 necrotic damage at the start of each of their turns for a number of rounds equal to your Constitution modifier (minimum 1). A creature can repeat the saving throw at the end of each turn, ending the effect on a success.
You can use this feature a number of times equal to your Constitution modifier (minimum 1), and you regain all expended uses when you finish a long rest.
6th Level - Putrid Resilience
You become immune to poison damage and the poisoned condition. When you take necrotic damage, you can use your reaction to regain hit points equal to half the damage taken (minimum 1). You can use this reaction once per turn.
7th Level - Death Sight
You can see normally in darkness, both magical and nonmagical, to a distance of 60 feet. As an action, you can sense the presence and location of undead within 60 feet of you for 1 minute. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a short rest.
9th Level - Aura of Decay
While berserking, hostile creatures within 10 feet of you have disadvantage on Constitution saving throws. When a hostile creature within this aura is reduced to 0 hit points, you regain hit points equal to your Constitution modifier (minimum 1).
10th Level - Enhanced Withering Touch
Your withering touch becomes more potent. The damage increases to 1d6 necrotic damage, and the DC increases by 2. Additionally, you can cast detect poison and disease at will.
11th Level - Spore Cloud
As an action, you can release toxic spores in a 15-foot radius centered on yourself. All hostile creatures in the area must make a Constitution saving throw. On failure, they take 2d8 poison damage and are poisoned for 1 minute. On success, they take half damage and are not poisoned. Poisoned creatures can repeat the save at the end of each turn, ending the effect on a success. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a short rest.
14th Level - Corrosive Presence
While berserking, your attacks against objects and structures deal double damage. When a creature hits you with a nonmagical weapon while you're berserking, the weapon takes a permanent -1 penalty to damage rolls (armor takes -1 to AC if they hit with natural weapons or unarmed strikes). If a penalty reduces an item to -5, it is destroyed. Magic items are immune to this effect.
15th Level - Champion of Rot
Your berserk transforms you into a vessel of decay. While berserking:
You have resistance to necrotic damage
Your swamp’s embrace bonus improves to 2d4 damage per attack with a melee weapon
Your aura of decay radius increases to 15 feet. Hostile creatures that start their turn in your aura take 1 necrotic damage.
17th Level - Domain of Blight
You can transform a 100-foot radius area into corrupted swampland for 4 hours. The area becomes difficult terrain for hostile creatures, you have advantage on attack rolls within it, and hostile creatures take 1d4 poison damage at the start of their turn while in the area. The transformation creates pools of stagnant water and twisted vegetation that provide total cover at your discretion. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a long rest.
18th Level - Lord of Decay 
Your withering touch no longer has limited uses while berserking—every melee hit automatically applies the curse. Once per long rest, you can assume the mantle of Gibbora for 1 minute. During this transformation, you become a living embodiment of decay and entropy. You gain the following benefits:
You are immune to all damage except radiant and force damage.
Hostile creatures that start their turn within 15 feet of you take 2d6 necrotic damage. Creatures that die from necrotic damage you deal to them cannot be resurrected by spells of 6th level or lower.
When you hit an undead or plant creature with a melee attack, if it has less than half of its remaining hit points, you may choose to drop its hit points to 0 instead of dealing normal damage.
You can make contact and move through solid objects as if they were difficult terrain, causing them to rapidly age and crumble as you pass. Magical weapons and armor are now affected by corrosive presence. Touching nonmagical weapons or armor immediately sets the corrosive presence penalty to -5.

Bashani
The Bashani dwell in the shadowed depths of the Veldt's western forest floor, where massive trees stretch impossibly high overhead, blocking out most sunlight. They are a people of the depths - both of the forest floor and of the cold, dark waters that pool between the massive root systems. Their rivalry with the tree-dwelling Asurani runs deeper than mere territorial disputes; it is a fundamental opposition of philosophies about where power truly lies.
Their brand radiates a subtle dark blue-purple color, like deep ocean water seen through twilight. The markings flow across their skin in wave-like patterns, as if currents move beneath their flesh. When they enter their berserk state, these markings seem to pulse with the rhythm of deep ocean tides, and the air around them grows cold and damp.
According to Bashani mythology, Basha was once a celestial being of great beauty and power who dwelt in the highest heavens. However, Basha was cast down into the deepest ocean trenches, where the crushing depths and eternal darkness corrupted the angel's divine nature. Now Basha grants power to those who embrace the cold depths, teaching that true strength comes not from reaching toward the light, but from mastering the darkness that lies beneath all things.
The Bashani have adapted to life in perpetual twilight, developing enhanced senses and an affinity for cold, damp environments. They are expert fishers and swimmers, building their settlements in the flooded hollows between massive tree roots. Their warriors train by diving into freezing underground pools, learning to fight while holding their breath in the crushing darkness of underwater caverns.
Game Features
1st Level - Deep Current
You have a swimming speed equal to your walking speed and can hold your breath for 15 + your Constitution modifier minutes. You have resistance to cold damage. While berserking, you emanate a freezing, crushing pressure in a 5-foot radius—this area becomes difficult terrain for hostile creatures, and your melee attacks deal an additional 1 cold damage.
2nd Level - Tidal Instincts
You have advantage on initiative rolls and can't be surprised while conscious. You gain proficiency in Athletics if you don't already have it, or expertise if you do. Your movement speed increases by 5 feet.
3rd Level - Crushing Grasp
While berserking, when you hit with a melee attack, you can attempt to grapple the target as a bonus action. Creatures grappled by you take 1d4 bludgeoning damage at the start of their turn from crushing pressure. You can use this feature a number of times equal to your proficiency bonus, and you regain all expended uses when you finish a short or long rest.
6th Level - Pressure Adaptation
You gain resistance to bludgeoning damage. While berserking, you cannot be knocked prone by effects of your level or lower, and forced movement against you is reduced by 10 feet (minimum 0).
7th Level - Abyssal Sight
Your darkvision increases to 120 feet, and you can see normally in magical darkness within 60 feet. You can sense the location of any creature within 30 feet that is touching the same body of water as you.
9th Level - Tidal Surge
As an action, you can create a crushing wave in a 20-foot cone. All creatures in the area must make a Strength saving throw (DC 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Constitution modifier). On failure, they are knocked prone and take 2d6 bludgeoning damage. On success, they take half damage and are not knocked prone. The area becomes difficult terrain for 1 minute. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a long rest.
10th Level - Deep Current Strike
When you hit with a melee attack while berserking, you can push the target up to 15 feet away from you. If they hit a wall or solid obstacle, they take an additional 1d6 bludgeoning damage. You can use this feature a number of times equal to your proficiency bonus, and you regain all expended uses when you finish a short or long rest.
11th Level - Leviathan's Resilience
You gain immunity to cold damage. While berserking, when you take damage, you can use your reaction to create a shockwave. Choose one creature within 15 feet—they must make a Constitution saving throw or be stunned until the end of their next turn. Once you use this reaction, you can't use it again until you finish a short or long rest.
14th Level - Oceanic Domain
You can create a 20-foot radius zone of crushing pressure centered on yourself for 1 minute. Hostile creatures in this area have their movement speed halved and take 1d6 bludgeoning damage at the start of their turn. The zone moves with you. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a long rest.
15th Level - Champion of the Deep
Your connection to the depths manifests physically while berserking. While berserking:
Your reach increases by 5 feet.
Your melee attacks deal an additional 1d4 cold damage. 
You can breathe water and air equally. You gain tremorsense of 10 feet while touching the same body of water as other creatures.
17th Level - Master of Depths
Once per long rest, you can channel the power of ocean trenches for 1 minute. You can move through water as if it were air and have a swim speed of 60 feet. As an action, you can create a pressurized water blast in a 40-foot line that is 5 feet wide, dealing 3d8 bludgeoning damage (Dexterity save for half).
18th Level - Improved Oceanic Domain 
Your oceanic domain resembles the presence of Basha himself. You can now fill a 40-foot radius with supernatural water for 1 minute. The area is heavily obscured for enemies, they move at half speed, and take 1d6 cold damage  + 1d6 bludgeoning damage at the start of their turn. Fire damage is reduced by half in the area. If a creature is knocked prone or pushed outside your oceanic domain, they are stunned during their next turn. You can use this feature twice every long rest.

Asurani
High above the forest floor, in the swaying canopy of the impossibly tall trees of the Veldt, dwell the Asurani. They are a people obsessed with height, light, and the boundless sky above. Their settlements are built on platforms hundreds to thousands of meters above the ground, connected by rope bridges and giant leaves that sway in the constant wind. They view the Bashani below with a mixture of pity and contempt, seeing them as creatures who have chosen to wallow in darkness rather than reach for the light.
Their brand burns bright orange and yellow like captured sunlight beneath the skin. The markings spread across their bodies in patterns reminiscent of feathers or flames, seeming to flicker and dance when they move. During their berserk state, these markings blaze with brilliant light.
The demon Asura, according to Asurani oral tradition, was once trapped in the depths of the Violet sea. The demon broke free from his prison and stole the wings of a celestial being, reaching the skies in a burst of glory and cursing the victims who witnessed his ascent.
Asurani culture revolves around concepts of elevation, both physical and spiritual. They believe that height brings one closer to divine truth. Asurani berserkers develop remarkable balance and acrobatic skills by fighting on narrow beams hundreds of feet in the air. 
Game Features
1st Level - Skybound Heritage
You have a climbing speed equal to your walking speed and resistance to fire damage. You take no damage from falls of 20 feet or less, and can reduce fall damage by an amount equal to 5 × your berserker level. While berserking, your weapons shed bright light in a 10-foot radius and dim light for an additional 10 feet, and your melee attacks deal an additional 1 fire damage.
2nd Level - Aerial Grace
You gain proficiency in Acrobatics. If you're already proficient, you gain expertise instead. You have advantage on saving throws against being knocked prone, and your long jump distance is tripled while your high jump distance is doubled.
3rd Level - Blazing Assault
While berserking, when you score a critical hit with a melee attack, you may set the target on fire, taking 1d6 fire damage at the start of each turn until they use an action to extinguish the flames or until the fire is extinguished by other means. You can use this feature a number of times equal to your proficiency bonus, and you regain all expended uses when you finish a long rest.
6th Level - Flame Wings
While berserking, ethereal wings of fire manifest from your shoulders. You gain a fly speed of 25 feet, but you must end your turn on solid ground or begin falling. If you attack a creature while flying above them, you deal an additional 1d4 fire damage.
7th Level - Solar Sight
Bright light doesn't impose disadvantage on your Perception checks, and you can see clearly up to twice the normal range in bright light. You can detect invisible creatures within 30 feet—they appear as faint, shimmering outlines but still benefit from being invisible.
9th Level - Diving Strike
When you move at least 20 feet straight toward a target and hit with a melee attack, you deal an additional 1d8 damage and the target must make a Strength saving throw (DC 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Strength modifier) or be knocked prone. If you were flying when you made this attack, the damage increases to 2d8. You can use this feature a number of times equal to your proficiency bonus, and you regain all expended uses when you finish a short or long rest.

10th Level - Flame Mastery
You become immune to fire damage. Your blazing assault fire damage increases to 1d8, and you can cast burning hands at 3rd level once per short rest without expending a spell slot (Constitution is your spellcasting ability).
11th Level - Solar Flare
As an action, you can release blinding solar energy in a 20-foot radius centered on yourself. All hostile creatures in the area must make a Constitution saving throw (DC 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Constitution modifier) or be blinded until the end of their next turn and take 2d6 radiant damage. On a successful save, they take half damage and are not blinded. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a short or long rest.
14th Level - Meteor
As an action, you can launch yourself up to 80 feet to any point you can see, igniting upon landing. All creatures within 15 feet of your landing point must make a Dexterity saving throw (DC 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Constitution modifier) or take 5d8 fire damage (half on success). The area becomes difficult terrain for 1 minute from smoldering embers. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a long rest.
15th Level - Champion of the Sky
Your mastery over flame and flight becomes pronounced while berserking. You gain the following benefits:
You are immune to fire damage
You gain a fly speed of 40 feet with no restriction to land on the ground, and you can hover. 
Your melee attacks have an additional 5 feet of reach as blazing energy extends from your weapons
You shed bright light in a 15-foot radius.
17th Level - Lord of the Burning Sky
Your fly speed increases to 60 feet, and you can carry one willing creature of your size or smaller while flying at full speed. You can cast fireball at 6th level twice per long rest without expending spell slots (Constitution is your spellcasting ability).
18th Level - Celestial Ascension 
Once per long rest, you can enter a state of angelic transcendence for 1 minute. You shed bright light in a 30-foot radius and dim light for an additional 30 feet. You have resistance to all damage except cold and necrotic. As a bonus action, you can teleport up to 60 feet, dealing 1d8 fire damage to all creatures within 5 feet of both your departure and arrival points, and your attacks deal an additional 1d6 radiant damage.

Orashkans
The Orashkans are the hardy nomads of Bisengal's northwestern badlands, a region transformed into a hellish wasteland by their patron's final act of madness. The landscape bears the scars of Orashka's corruption: twisted rock formations that resemble screaming faces, water sources that run red with mineral deposits, and wildlife mutated into grotesque parodies of their former selves. The Orashkans have adapted to this harsh environment, becoming as fierce and unpredictable as the land they call home.
Their brand appears as black veins that throb and pulse beneath their skin, becoming more pronounced during times of strong emotion. These veins seem to carry something other than blood - a corruption that spreads through their bodies like a living infection. When they enter their berserk state, this corruption manifests physically, transforming them into monstrous amalgamations of human and beast.
The legend of Orashka serves as both inspiration and warning to the tribe. Once a mortal human driven by ambition, Orashka made a pact with a devil for power and knowledge. For years he ruled through fear and might, but the devil's influence slowly ate away at his sanity. In his final moments of lucidity, Orashka chose to release all of the devil's accumulated power in a single catastrophic event, preferring to destroy everything rather than let the devil claim his soul completely. This act of defiant madness created the badlands and cursed those in his wake.
Orashkan society is built around survival in an impossibly hostile environment. They are expert hunters of the mutated megafauna that roam the badlands, using every part of their kills for food, tools, and shelter. Their nomadic lifestyle is dictated by the ever-shifting dangers of their homeland. They have learned to read the signs of their corrupted land, following migration patterns of mutant beasts and avoiding areas where the corruption runs deepest.
Game Features
3rd Level - Bestial Transformation While in berserk, you undergo a partial transformation into a monstrous creature. You can choose the type of beast you resemble (wolf, bear, boar, etc.) when you first gain this feature, and this choice is permanent. You grow natural weapons (claws, fangs, horns, etc.) that deal 1d4 + your Strength modifier of slashing, piercing or bludgeoning damage. These weapons are treated as magical weapons. You can make an attack with your natural weapons as a bonus action.
2nd Level - Predator's Instincts
You have advantage on Wisdom (Perception) checks that rely on hearing or smell, and can track creatures by scent if you move at half speed. You gain proficiency in Survival. If you're already proficient, you gain expertise instead. Your movement speed increases by 5 feet.
3rd Level - Adaptive Mutation
When you take acid, cold, fire, lightning, or thunder damage, you gain resistance to that damage type until you finish a long rest. During a long rest, you can spend time adapting to your environment. Choose one: 
Resistance to extreme heat or cold for 24 hours, 
the ability to breathe underwater for 24 hours, or 
advantage on Constitution saving throws against disease and poison for 24 hours.
6th Level - Pack Leader
You can cast animal friendship once per long rest without expending a spell slot, but only targeting beasts. While berserking, when a beast or monstrosity with Intelligence 4 or lower starts its turn within 30 feet of you, you can use your reaction to force it to make a Wisdom saving throw (DC 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Constitution modifier). On failure, it is charmed by you until the start of its next turn.
7th Level - Apex Senses
You have advantage on saving throws against being frightened or charmed. Your natural weapons deal an additional 1 damage, and you gain darkvision to 60 feet. If you already have darkvision, its range increases by 30 feet instead.
9th Level - Territorial Dominance
As an action, you can mark a 80-foot radius area as your hunting ground for 10 minutes. Within this area, you have advantage on attack rolls and Stealth checks, and the first time each turn that you deal damage to a hostile creature in this area, they take an additional 1d4 psychic damage. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a short or long rest.
10th Level - Evolved Predator
Your natural weapons deal 1d6 base damage instead of 1d4. When you attack with your natural weapons as your bonus action, you now may attack twice.
11th Level - Rapid Regeneration
At the start of your turn, if you have fewer than half your hit points and haven't taken radiant damage since your last turn, you regain hit points equal to your Constitution modifier (minimum 1).
14th Level - Call of the Wild
You can cast conjure animals at 5th level once per long rest without expending a spell slot. The summoned creatures appear somewhat corrupted and twisted, gaining resistance to one damage type of your choice. They remain for 10 minutes and obey your commands without question. Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a long rest.
15th Level - Champion of Monstrosity
Your berserk transforms you into a truly monstrous creature. While in berserk, you gain the following benefits:
Your size increases by one category (Small to Medium, Medium to Large, etc.). Worn armor grows with you.
Your tough hide increases your AC equal to your proficiency bonus.
Your Strength score increases by 2.
17th Level - Orashka's Madness
Once per long rest, you can embrace primal corruption for 1 minute. You have advantage on ability checks, natural weapon attacks always deal maximum damage, and you gain resistance to bludgeoning, piercing, and slashing damage. However, you must use your action each turn to attack the nearest creature (friendly or hostile), though you choose what attacks to make and can use abilities. When this effect ends, you gain one level of exhaustion.
18th Level - Improved Call of the Wild Once per long rest, you can summon powerful beasts to aid you. Your call of the wild ability now functions as the conjure animals spell cast at 8th level, and those creatures gain resistances to two damage types of your choice. You can use this feature twice every long rest.
